  "text": "The migration from the legacy Kafka consumer API (kafka.consumer.ConsumerConnector) to the new KafkaConsumer API is represented through a sophisticated internal architecture change in apache/kafka. While the old ConsumerConnector interface is no longer present in the current codebase (it was removed in favor of the newer API), the current implementation demonstrates a thoughtful migration strategy using a delegation pattern.\n\nThe new API is centered around KafkaConsumer (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/KafkaConsumer.java), which implements the Consumer interface (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/Consumer.java). However, the actual implementation is delegated to one of two internal implementations through the ConsumerDelegateCreator factory (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/ConsumerDelegateCreator.java):\n\n1. ClassicKafkaConsumer (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/ClassicKafkaConsumer.java) - Provides backward compatibility with the classic group protocol (pre-KIP-848). This implementation uses synchronous coordination patterns where offset commits are handled through ConsumerCoordinator with methods like coordinator.commitOffsetsSync() for synchronous commits and coordinator.commitOffsetsAsync() for asynchronous commits.\n\n2. AsyncKafkaConsumer (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/AsyncKafkaConsumer.java) - Implements the new consumer group protocol (KIP-848) using an event-driven architecture. Instead of direct coordinator calls, it uses ApplicationEventHandler to queue AsyncCommitEvent and SyncCommitEvent objects that are processed asynchronously by background threads.\n\nKEY BEHAVIORAL DIFFERENCES IN OFFSET MANAGEMENT:\n\n(1) Synchronous vs. Event-Driven Architecture: \n- ClassicKafkaConsumer uses direct method calls: commitSync() calls coordinator.commitOffsetsSync() directly and blocks until completion.\n- AsyncKafkaConsumer uses event queuing: commitSync() creates a CompletableFuture and enqueues a SyncCommitEvent to be processed by background threads, then waits for the future to complete.\n\n(2) Offset Commit Request Handling:\n- Both implementations now delegate commit operations to CommitRequestManager (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/CommitRequestManager.java), which manages the actual OffsetCommit protocol requests to the broker.\n- ClassicKafkaConsumer uses this through ConsumerCoordinator which internally uses CommitRequestManager.\n- AsyncKafkaConsumer uses CommitRequestManager directly through its event-driven background thread.\n\n(3) Offset Fetching and Position Management:\n- Both use OffsetsRequestManager (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/OffsetsRequestManager.java) for managing ListOffset requests to retrieve offsets from brokers.\n- Both use OffsetFetcher (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/OffsetFetcher.java) as a utility for offset fetching operations.\n- Both use SubscriptionState (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/SubscriptionState.java) to track partition assignments and current fetch positions.\n\n(4) Callback Handling:\n- ClassicKafkaConsumer immediately invokes offset commit callbacks within the application thread.\n- AsyncKafkaConsumer uses OffsetCommitCallbackInvoker to queue callbacks for execution, providing better isolation between user code and the consumer.\n\n(5) Configuration Strategy:\n- The choice between implementations is controlled by the group.protocol configuration setting.\n- Setting group.protocol=\"consumer\" activates AsyncKafkaConsumer (new protocol).\n- Setting group.protocol=\"classic\" (or not setting it) uses ClassicKafkaConsumer for backward compatibility.\n\nThe ConsumerDelegate interface (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/ConsumerDelegate.java) enables this pluggable architecture, extending the Consumer interface with internal methods for testing and framework use.\n\nIn Apache Camel (components/camel-kafka/src/main/java/org/apache/camel/component/kafka/KafkaConsumer.java), the migration is transparent - Camel's KafkaConsumer wraps the Apache Kafka Consumer API and automatically benefits from whichever implementation (Classic or Async) is selected based on the configuration."
}

